                "name": "Manny Goldman",
                "href": "/profile/Manny-Goldman"
            },
            "answer_text": "A consistent and high level of research productivity, evidenced by publication of peer-reviewed papers in leading journals of the field. Expertise and activity in an area considered important to the field and to the base of human knowledge. Recognition of research credentials reflected by successful applications for grant funding, especially from federal organizations like NIH and NSF. Having a strong reputation as a leader in your field, attested to not only by colleagues at MIT, but also by recognized leaders in the field at other top institutions (e.g., Harvard, Princeton, Yale, Columbia, Cornell, Stanford, Berkeley, etc.). In addition to the above, evidence of some success as a teacher, both in the classroom and in the laboratory, and some record of service to the institution and the community (e.g., serving on editorial boards of prominent journals in the field, participating in administrative duties in the department and the school). There aren\u2019t a whole lot of people that can make that cut. ",
